and reloading secure settings, the Kubernetes resources that were added for the new tier (the StatefulSet, Service, and ConfigMap), and the keystore modifications that would need to be cleaned up on each node before reloading the settings.\n\nI'm also reconsidering what \"index settings\" means in this context—it might actually refer to the node-level settings in the ConfigMap like the zone awareness attribute, or possibly cluster-level allocation awareness settings that were applied earlier but aren't visible in the current state since any test indices were already removed.\n\nLooking at what's actually been changed from a default Elasticsearch 8.11.1 setup, I can see the snapshot repository for MinIO, the S3 keystore credentials, the new StatefulSet with zone attributes and restricted roles, the associated ConfigMap and Service, and possibly the HTTP compression setting. For the rollback script, I need to systematically remove these additions: delete the snapshot repository through the API, strip out the S3 keystore entries from each node, reload the secure settings, scale down and delete the new StatefulSet, and clean up all the related resources.\n\nBut I'm realizing the task specifically asks to revert \"non-default settings back to Elasticsearch defaults\" — which could mean just the API-level changes like the snapshot repository and keystore entries, not necessarily the Kubernetes infrastructure changes. However, for a truly comprehensive rollback that restores the cluster to its pre-modification state, I should include both the Elasticsearch API changes and the Kubernetes-level additions in the script. So those custom attributes and restricted roles are the non-default settings I need to account for in the rollback. I'll write a comprehensive script that safely reverts the snapshot repository configuration, cluster-level S3 credentials, node attributes, and role restrictions, with dry-run options and confirmation prompts since this needs to be reviewed befor